### Expected behavior

`details.webContentsId` in WebRequest.onHeadersReceived callback should be populated, as is [documented](https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/master/docs/api/web-request.md#webrequestonheadersreceivedfilter-listener). (Although it does say optional, but it's not clear when it would be missing.)

### Actual behavior

`details.webContentsId` is undefined.

### How to reproduce

Ran this snippet in Electron Fiddle, identified the change was introduced between [2.0.12 and 3.0.0-beta.1](https://github.com/electron/electron/compare/v3.0.0-beta.1...v2.0.12).

```javascript
const {app, BrowserWindow} = require('electron')

function createWindow () {
  const mainWindow = new BrowserWindow()
  mainWindow
      .webContents
      .session
      .webRequest
      .onHeadersReceived((details, cb) => {
        const id = details.webContentsId;
        console.log('webContentsId:', id);
        // Exit with 1 (fail) if id is missing,
        // or 0 (pass) if id is present
        app.exit(Number(id == undefined));
      })
  mainWindow.loadURL('http://example.com')
}

app.on('ready', createWindow)
```

A CSP header setting described in [security.md](https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/9262731f2cc991d9ba97e0e977007e0f39da4983/docs/tutorial/security.md#csp-http-header) is incorrect. It does not actually emit the CSP header. 

**Current Code:**
```js
const { session } = require('electron')

session.defaultSession.webRequest.onHeadersReceived((details, callback) => {
  callback({ responseHeaders: `default-src 'none'` })
})
```

**Proposed Fix:**
```js
const { session } = require('electron')

session.defaultSession.webRequest.onHeadersReceived((details, callback) => {
  callback({
    responseHeaders: {
      ...details.responseHeaders,
      "Content-Security-Policy": ["default-src 'none'"]
    }
  })
})
```

It's great that https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/10335 is now implemented.

As a follow-up feature, is there also a way to get the selected file format back, e.g. in the callback? There is no way to tell what the user selected, if two formats have the same extension.

